ng?” It also recognizes that teaching is a dynamic process that requires critical reflection and thoughtful adjustment in order to foster a supportive artistic environment. Instead of offering rigid formulas, this book is centered on practice—the actual doing and making of teaching artist work. Experience-based and full of heart, the Teaching Artist Handbook will encourage artists of every experience level to create an original and innovative practice that inspires students and the artist.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aArtxStudy and teachingzUnited States. 0aArts in educationzUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh1 aBarniskis, Becca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCox, Barbara Hackett, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aDaichendt, G. James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHackett Cox, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaffe, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226256917423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226256917.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles